<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="21">
<pageBreakToken pageId="10" pageNumber="21" start="start">Genus</pageBreakToken>
<taxonomicName LSID="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4AC287DC-4E88-4043-BA17-880E84883276" authority="Glöer &amp; Pešić, 2012" authorityName="Glöer &amp; Pešić" authorityYear="2012" class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Sarkhia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sarkhia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="10" pageNumber="21" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">Sarkhia</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="10" pageNumber="21">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="21" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Shell elongated conical. Penis simple, broad at the basis and tapered at the distal end, with a black pigmentation mark. The tentacles are cylindrical.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="21" type="type species">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Type species.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicName genus="Sarkia" lsidName="" pageId="10" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="sarabensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Sarkia sarabensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. n.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="21" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Named after the region where the species was collected.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="21" type="differential diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Differential diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="21">
The genus seems to be closely related to 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Pseudamnicola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="10" pageNumber="21" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Pseudamnicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(in the following, in parentheses), but theunique morphology of the penis, broad at the basis and tapered at the distal end (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Kaskakia khorrasanensis sp. n. a shell b penis in situ c-d penis (c: dorsal view, d: ventral view)." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/20814" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Figs 10b-c</figureCitation>
), with a black pigmentation mark (vs. broad and elongated triangular penis), and the presence of broad cylindrical tentacles (slim cylindrical tentacles) will separate the new genus from 
<taxonomicName class="Gastropoda" family="Hydrobiidae" genus="Pseudamnicola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="10" pageNumber="21" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Pseudamnicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
